# .forge/resilience.config — P2 single-session resilience tunables.
#
# A bash-sourceable KEY=value file. The relaunch loop, the Stop / SessionStart
# hooks, the liveness watchdog, and the continuation helper all `source` this to
# resolve their thresholds — so a project tunes resilience here, not by editing
# scripts. This file is COMMITTED to git (the runtime dirs it points at —
# .forge/continuation/ and .forge/heartbeat/ — are gitignored, this is not).
#
# Sourced, not executed: no shebang, no logic, only `KEY=value` lines and
# comments. Keep it that way — `source`-ing arbitrary logic is a footgun.
#
# Shipped defaults are the design doc's §Q1 table. Override per project as needed.
# See docs/design/p2-single-session-resilience.md §Q1 / §Q3 for rationale.

# ── Context-window thresholds (design doc §Q1) ───────────────────────────────
# Percent of the context window used. The relaunch loop reads real token counts
# from each generation's `claude -p --output-format json` `.usage` block and
# compares against the role's warn / hard pair:
#   used < warn          → relaunch normally
#   warn <= used < hard  → relaunch, signal next generation to hand off promptly
#   used >= hard         → must hand off this generation; no generation starts
#                          that would run past hard without a handoff
#
# Orchestrator = Tier 0 / Tier 1, long-lived. Its context is load-bearing state,
# so it hands off early (40/50). These numbers are proven in the temper skill's
# context-discipline section — the north-star doc says do not raise them.
FORGE_ORCH_WARN_PCT=40
FORGE_ORCH_HARD_PCT=50

# Worker = Tier 2, ephemeral. Its context is mostly scratch and it returns a
# structured sentinel, so a late handoff costs little — more runway (50/60),
# still clear of Claude Code's ~75% auto-compact trigger.
FORGE_WORKER_WARN_PCT=50
FORGE_WORKER_HARD_PCT=60

# Total context window size, in tokens, used as the denominator when turning
# `.usage` token counts into a percentage. Adjust if your model's window differs.
FORGE_CONTEXT_WINDOW_TOKENS=200000

# ── Relaunch-loop throttle ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Minimum seconds between relaunches. Pairs with launchd's own throttle: this
# guards handoff-thrash spin at the loop level, launchd guards process-crash
# thrash at the supervisor level.
FORGE_THROTTLE_SECONDS=10

# ── Thrash circuit breaker (design doc §2 / §Q3) ─────────────────────────────
# Q3's monotonic generation counter makes handoff thrash trivial to see: if more
# than FORGE_THRASH_MAX_GENERATIONS handoffs happen within
# FORGE_THRASH_WINDOW_SECONDS, the relaunch loop trips its breaker and exits
# non-zero so a human is alerted. An infinite hand-off loop is a bug, not a
# state to spin in.
FORGE_THRASH_MAX_GENERATIONS=5
FORGE_THRASH_WINDOW_SECONDS=300

# ── Liveness watchdog ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Heartbeat age, in seconds, past which the watchdog treats a session as hung
# (not working) — captures diagnostics and kills the wedged claude process so
# the crash-recovery path takes over. The Stop hook touches
# .forge/heartbeat/<slug> on every fire.
FORGE_HEARTBEAT_TIMEOUT_SECONDS=900

# ── Continuation retention ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# How many gen-NNN.md generations to keep per session slug. The continuation
# helper prunes older generations past this cap after each write. Retained
# generations give the audit trail / recovery point the design doc §Q3 wants;
# the cap keeps the directory bounded.
FORGE_RETENTION_CAP=20
